reviewText: Talky introduction to a mental condition then little known to the public features stilted staging and camera work adequate to get the job done, basically a filmed radio play
I purchase tis movie to show at the assisted living home my father lived at they all loved it
Nicely handled B noir melodrama from Arch Oboler. Daring in its way.

The marvelous Arch Oboler of LIGHTS OUT fame practically put this whole piece together himself for MGM in 1945, based on a play of his, and the results are a wonderfully quickly paced little B horror-thriller about a woman with a most bizarre split personality.  Phyllis Thaxter, Edmund Gwenn, and Stephen (nee Horace) McNally all turn in fine performances here and convey the complexities of the situation nicely.  I highly recommend this to all who love good psychological horror films.  Enjoy!!
